    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Pseudoacanthocereus brasiliensis are flavonoids, phenolic acids, and triterpenoids, which have been identified due to their antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties. Flavonoids such as quercetin and kaempferol have been shown to exhibit antioxidant activity by scavenging free radicals and reducing oxidative stress. Phenolic acids like ferulic acid and sinapic acid have been found to possess anti-inflammatory properties, which may contribute to their potential in treating inflammatory diseases. Triterpenoids, including acanthoside B and acanthoside D, have been demonstrated to exhibit antimicrobial activity against various microorganisms, highlighting their potential in wound healing and infection prevention. These constituents have been isolated and characterized through various phytochemical studies, providing evidence for the medicinal properties of Pseudoacanthocereus brasiliensis.",
