    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Pseudoacanthocereus brasiliensis are infusion, tincture, tea, salve, and decoction. Infusion is typically a liquid preparation made by steeping the plant material in hot water, often used for its antioxidant and anti-inflammatory properties. Tincture involves the extraction of the plant's bioactive compounds using a solvent, usually ethanol or glycerin, and is commonly used for its antimicrobial and antifungal effects. Salve, a topical application, involves mixing the plant's extract with a carrier oil, often used to soothe skin irritations and wounds, while decoction involves boiling the plant material to release its active compounds, often used for its anti-inflammatory and antiseptic properties. These preparations are often used to treat various health conditions, including wounds, skin irritations, and infections, due to the plant's rich content of flavonoids, alkaloids, and other bioactive compounds.",
